## Dogfooding Verdict

The Ralph Loop is validated at every Qwen3.5 weight class tested. The explicit state machine keeps the agent on track whether the model is 0.8B running locally or Claude Opus running in the cloud — it drives the model through states, it doesn't rely on the model to self-sequence.

**4B is the practical floor for reliable local tool use.** It passes all 13 tasks with correct answers, uses shell arithmetic rather than hallucinating numeric results, and recovers cleanly from tool errors. The 4B model at Q8_0 quantization on a 16-core server handles the full agentic loop — read, write, verify, self-correct — at 10–65s per call with zero cloud dependency.

**9B is faster but less trustworthy.** The additional capacity makes the 9B more likely to answer from memory rather than running the required command. For tasks where ground truth matters (file contents, line counts, exact constant values), the 4B is the better agent.

**2B is viable for lightweight tasks.** Lookup, write, and execute tasks work reliably. Multi-step grep pipelines and tasks requiring coordinated tool sequencing exceed its reliable operating range.

```bash
# Fully local agentic stack — zero API keys, zero cloud cost
igllama api Qwen3.5-4B-Q8_0.gguf \
  --port 8092 --no-think --max-tokens 512 \
  --threads 4 --threads-batch 16 --ctx-size 2048 --mlock &
powerglide run --agent local4b "summarise what src/orchestrator/swarm.zig does"
```

